The preparation of the financial statements in conformity with adopted IFRS requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities at the date of the  financial statements and the reported amounts of  revenues and expenses during the year then ended. Management bases its estimates on historical experience and various other assumptions that are believed to be reasonable under the circumstances.  Actual results may differ from those estimates.


Estimates are used in accounting for allowances for uncollectible receivables, depreciation, amortisation and Impairment, share-based payments, pensions, taxes and contingencies.  Estimates and assumptions are reviewed periodically and the effects of revisions are reflected in the financial statements in the period that an adjustment is determined to be required.


Management discussed with the Audit Committee the development, selection and disclosure of the  group's critical accounting policies and estimates and the application of these policies and estimates.


Significant accounting judgements in applying the group's accounting policies have been applied by the group in order to prepare the consolidated financial statements with respect to the value of goodwill as described In note 12.


In applying the group's accounting policies the Directors are often required to make judgements.  Those judgements which have had the most significant effect on the amounts recognised in the financial statements, and to which the Directors believe it is appropriate to draw the reader's attention, are summarised below:


Valuation of constituent businesses


Whilst the value of the constituent businesses of the group is a matter of considerable commercial sensitivity, the accounting rules require the directors to consider the carrying value for the purposes of the annual report.  In order to effect the reorganisation of the group in May of 2009, the Board of Directors appointed independent valuers to establish a third party view of the value of the businesses at that time.  The range of those valuations reflected, inter alia, the considerable uncertainties surrounding the businesses at the time, all of which are now resolved.  The Board has nonetheless taken a prudent view and, mindful that the balance sheet is not a valuation statement, has reflected those valuations in these accounts.


Uncertainties


In preparing the financial statements the Directors are also required to make estimates and assumptions about matters that can be uncertain as they are subject to external factors.  The Directors have reviewed these, and all other assumptions and estimates used in the preparation of the financial statements, and do not believe that there is a significant risk of a material adjustment arising within the next financial year to the carrying amount of any assets or liabilities as a result of any reasonably likely change In these assumptions and estimates.

Accounting Policies


Basis of preparation


The significant accounting policies of the group and parent Company are set out below


The group's annual consolidated financial statements for the year ended 30 September 2009 are prepared In accordance with International Financial Reporting Standards (IFRSs) adopted for use In the European Union (adopted IFRS) International Financial Reporting Interpretations Committee (IFRIC) interpretations and those parts of the Companies Act 2006 applicable to companies, reporting under IFRS The directors have elected to prepare the parent Company's financial statements on the same basis


Statement of compliance  

The financial statements have been prepared in accordance with adopted IFRS.


New standards and interpretations not yet applied 


The following new EU adopted standards, amendments to standards and interpretations were not effective for the year ended 30 September 2009, and have not been applied in preparing these financial statements.


IFRS 8 Operating Segments introduces the management approach to segment reporting.  IFRS 8, which becomes mandatory for the group's September 2010 financial statements, will require the disclosure of segment information based on internal reports regularly reviewed by the board and executive In order to assess each segment's performance and to allocate resources to them.  Currently the group presents segment information m respect of business segments (see note 1); these segments are not anticipated to change under the group's management approach


IFRIC 14 The Limit of a Defined Benefit Asset provides guidance on the amount of a pension asset that can be recognised as an asset.  It concludes that refunds and reductions in contributions are recognisable as assets if they can be realised at some point during the life of the pension plan.  The group does not consider this interpretation will have a material impact on the group's financial position. It will be effective for the group's September 2010 financial statements


Amendments to IAS 1 Presentation of Financial Statements A Revised Presentation proposes changing the content of the income statement and the statement of recognised income and expense and includes an opening balance sheet for all periods.  It will be effective for the group's September 2010 financial statements and will result In the renaming of the primary statements and the presentation of an opening balance sheet for the comparative period


Amendment to IAS 23 Borrowing Costs removes the choice of treatment for borrowing costs.  Under the revised standard borrowing costs must be capitalised where the criteria established have been met.  The group's existing accounting policy is to capitalise such costs, therefore the revised standard is not expected to have an Impact on the group's future financial statements


Amendment to IAS 27 Consolidated and Separate Financial Statements revises the accounting for parent's ownership interest in a subsidiary following the revision to IFRS 3 (see below).  This will be effective for the group's September 2010 financial statements


Amendment to IFRS 2 Share-based Payment Vesting Conditions and Cancellations changes the definition of vesting conditions and clarifies the accounting treatment of cancellation by either parties.  The definition of vesting conditions is now restricted to either service or performance conditions.  Any other conditions will be non-vesting conditions and will be factored into the fair value at the grant date.  These amendments will impact SAYE schemes.  The group is currently considering the potential Impact of this amendment.  This will be effective for the group's September 2010 financial statements


Revised IFRS 3 Business Combinations revises several significant areas.  In accounting for acquisitions it determines that the cost of Investment should reflect the fair value of the consideration received by the vendor and hence acquisition expenses should be expensed as incurred.  Pre-existing interests in a step acquisition must be re-measured to fair value when the acquirer obtains control with any resulting gain or loss being recognised in the income statement. The revised standard requires that contingent consideration is measured at fair value at the acquisition date, however subsequent revisions are recognised in the income statement.  Retrospective application is not required. This standard will potentially have a significant impact on the group's accounting for future acquisitions.  This will be effective for the group's September 2010 financial statements.


lFRIC 12 Service Concession Arrangements, IFRIC 13  Customer Loyalty Programmes, lFRIC 15 Agreements for the Construction of Real Estate, IFRIC 16 Hedges  of Net Investment In a Foreign Operation, IFRIC 17  Distributions of Non-cash Asset to Owners IFRIC 18  Transfer of Assets from Customers, and amendments to IAS 32 Puttable Financial Instruments , IAS 39   Eligible Hedged Items and IAS 1 Obligations Arising on  Liquidation will not have a material impact on the group


The Directors do not anticipate that the adoption of any of the above standards or interpretations will have a material impact on the group's accounts In the period of initial application


Significant sources of estimation uncertainty and critical accounting judgements in applying the group's accounting policies


The preparation of the financial statements in conformity with adopted IFRS requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities at the date of the  financial statements and the reported amounts of  revenues and expenses during the year then ended. Management bases its estimates on historical experience and various other assumptions that are believed to be reasonable under the circumstances.  Actual results may differ from those estimates.


Estimates are used in accounting for allowances for uncollectible receivables, depreciation, amortisation and Impairment, share-based payments, pensions, taxes and contingencies.  Estimates and assumptions are reviewed periodically and the effects of revisions are reflected in the financial statements in the period that an adjustment is determined to be required.


Management discussed with the Audit Committee the development, selection and disclosure of the  group's critical accounting policies and estimates and the application of these policies and estimates.


Significant accounting judgements in applying the group's accounting policies have been applied by the group in order to prepare the consolidated financial statements with respect to the value of goodwill as described in note 12.


Basis of accounting and consolidation


The financial statements have been prepared under the historical cost convention, as modified by the revaluation of certain financial instruments.


The consolidated financial statements include the accounts of the Company and all Its subsidiary undertakings including the Employee Share Ownership Plan (ESOP) Trust.


Intra-group balances and transactions, and any unrealised Income and gains arising from intra-group transactions are eliminated on consolidation.


The results of businesses or subsidiaries acquired or disposed of during the period are included In the consolidated income statement from/to the effective date of that acquisition or disposal.


The prior period comparatives are restated where appropriate to achieve a consistent classification of line items with the current period presentation. The only restatements in these financial statements are in respect of the discontinued operation.


 Discontinued Operations


In August 2009, DDDDD Subsidiary 5 Limited was placed into administration. Consequently the results of Division D within DDDDD Subsidiary 5 have been shown as a discontinued operation and the comparative income statement has been restated to show the discontinued operation separately from continuing operations.


Going Concern


The financial statements have been prepared on a going concern basis.


The Interim Statement released in May 2009 identified four specific risks which could impact the group's ability to continue as a Going Concern. The directors have reconsidered each of these risks.


Pension Fund Trustee approval was required to effect the restructure.  This was achieved by issuing shares in the Company following shareholders approval on 12 October 2009.


The terms of the reorganisation could be challenged.  DDDDD Subsidiary 5 Limited went into administration on 3 August 2009.  No challenge to the terms of the reorganisation has been made by the Administrators and the directors, having taken  legal advice, consider that the likelihood of a successful challenge is remote.


There could be a call on the cross guarantee.  A managed transition was completed when the Administrators sold the business to the successor wholesalers.  The banks have been paid In full and the cross guarantee has lapsed.


The other business had to renegotiate terms of funding or find alternative sources of funding.


The Company announced on 3 August 2009 that DDDDD Subsidiary 5 Limited had been placed into administration.  The administration signalled the start of a 180 day period during which the banking facilities and security arrangements (including cross guarantees) of the remainder of the group needed to be renegotiated.


On 17 December 2009, the Company announced that It had entered Into agreements With Big Bank PLC to secure new finance facilities.


Big Bank provides the group's day-to-day banking requirements and provides a working capital facility of up to £7m.  The working capital facility is available for at least the next 24 months.  The Board is satisfied that the facilities are adequate based on the group's current working capital requirements.


The facilities are secured with fixed and floating charges over the assets of the principal subsidiaries.


The Directors have reviewed the financial forecasts, including sensitivity analysis on key assumptions and have concluded that the group has appropriate financing facilities in place to allow the group to operate for the foreseeable future and consider that the group is able to operate within the terms of those facilities.


Functional and presentation currency


The financial statements are presented in sterling which is also the Company's functional currency.  All financial information has been rounded to the nearest £0.1m.


Business combinations and goodwill


Following a business combination (acquisition), goodwill represents the surplus of the cost of acquisition over the fair values of the identifiable net assets of the business or subsidiary undertaking acquired.  Goodwill is capitalised as an asset and provision is made for any impairment.  It is not amortised but is reviewed for impairment at least annually.


Goodwill that had arisen on acquisitions prior to the date of transition to IFRS has been retained at the previous UK GAAP carrying amount (except where impaired).  Goodwill that had been written off to reserves under UK GAAP prior to 1998 has not been reinstated.


Upon the group's obtaining a controlling interest in a subsidiary undertaking the interest of any minority shareholders is stated at the minority's proportion of the fair values of the assets and liabilities recognised.  In the case of step acquisitions goodwill arising at the point of gaining a controlling interest is calculated by reference to the cost and fair value information at the date of each incremental purchase.  Where, subsequently, there are further Increases in the group's ownership, goodwill is calculated as the difference between the consideration paid for the additional interest and the current book value of the net assets of the subsidiary.


Associates and joint ventures


In the consolidated accounts, shares in associated undertakings and joint ventures are accounted for using the equity method of accounting.  The consolidated income statement includes the group's share of the post-tax profits of the associated undertakings.


Investments in associates are carried in the balance sheet at cost as adjusted by any post-acquisition changes in the group's share of the net assets of the associate less any provisions for impairment.  Goodwill relating to investments in associates is included as part of the carrying amount of the investment and is not amortised.


Intangible assets (other than goodwill)


Internally generated intangible assets, such as major business software developments, are recognised provided they generate future economic benefits and their costs are clearly identified.


Separately identifiable intangible assets acquired along with the purchase of businesses or subsidiary undertakings (for example, the value of contracts or customer lists) are recognised at their fair value.


All intangible assets are amortised over their useful lives, typically a maximum of 5 years, and provision is made for any impairment.


Property, plant and equipment


Property plant and equipment are stated in the balance sheet at historic cost less provision for depreciation and any impairment.  Cost includes expenditure that is directly attributable to the acquisition of the asset and bringing the asset to a working condition for its intended use.  The group does not capitalise borrowing costs.


Depreciation is provided on a straight-tine basis so as to write off the costs of assets over their useful lives, using the following rates:


Freehold and long-leasehold buildings: over 25 to 50 years


Short-leasehold buildings: over the remaining period of the lease


Fixtures, fittings, equipment:  15% on a straight line basis


motor vehicles:  25% on a straight line basis


Depreciation is not provided on freehold land or assets in the course of construction.


Assets held under finance leases are depreciated over their expected useful lives on the same basis as owned assets, or where shorter, over the term of the relevant lease.


Gains and losses on disposal of an item of property plant and equipment are determined by comparing the proceeds from disposal with the carrying amount and are recognised net within other operating income within the consolidated income statement.


Impairment reviews


At each balance sheet date, and such other time as there is any indication of impairment, the group reviews the carrying amounts of its tangible and intangible assets (including goodwill) to determine their recoverable amount.  If the carrying value is in excess of the recoverable amount the asset is then written down to its recoverable amount.


Recoverable amount is the higher of value in use or fair value less costs to sell.  In assessing value in use the estimated future cash flows are discounted to their present value using a pre-tax discount rate that reflects current market assessment of the time value of money and the risk specific to the asset. For an asset that does not generate largely independent cash inflows the recoverable amount is determined for the cash generating unit to which the asset belongs.


Where the asset does not generate cash flows that are independent from other assets, for example goodwill, the group allocates these assets to cash generating units.  Goodwill is allocated to cash generating units upon acquisition, based on the synergies expected to arise from the business combination.


All impairment losses are recognised in profit or loss.  Any cumulative loss in respect of an available-for-sale financial asset recognised previously in equity is transferred to profit or loss.


Leases


Leases are classified as finance leases whenever the terms of the lease transfer substantially all of the risks and rewards of ownership to the lessee.  All other leases are classified as operating leases.


Assets acquired under finance leases are capitalised and depreciated over the shorter  of the lease terms or their useful lives.


Rentals for operating leases are charged on a straight-line basis over the lease term.


Inventories


Inventories principally comprise finished goods with a rapid and high turnover


Financial instruments


Financial assets and financial liabilities are recognised on the group's balance sheet when the group becomes a party to the contractual obligations of the instrument.  Non-derivative financial instruments are recognised initially at fair value plus any directly attributable transaction costs


Equity instruments


Equity instruments issued by the Company (for example, DDDDD PLC 1p ordinary shares) are recorded at the proceeds received, net of direct issue costs.  An equity instrument is any contract that evidences a residual Interest In the assets of the group after deducting all of its liabilities.


Puttable equity instruments


Where equity instruments, including those held by minority interests, are puttable by the holders full provision is made for the obligation as a liability In the group balance sheet.


Investments in own shares


  Investments in own shares including those held by the ESOP Trust are shown as a component of equity (the reserve for treasury shares) rather than as assets.


Investments in other shares and securities


Investments in unquoted shares and securities (considered available for sale) are recorded at fair value which is derived from discounted cash flows.


Investments in quoted shares and securities are recorded at fair value.


Derivative financial instruments


Derivative financial instruments are held at fair value


Bank borrowings


Bank loans and overdrafts are recorded at fair value less transaction costs. Subsequently they are measured at amortised cost using the effective interest rate method.


Cash and cash equivalents


Cash and cash equivalents comprise cash balances and call deposits.  Bank overdrafts that are repayable on demand and form an integral part of the group's cash management are included as a component of cash and cash equivalents for the purpose of the statement of cash flows.


Trade payables and receivables


Trade receivables and trade payables do not carry any interest and are stated at their nominal value.  Provision is made for estimated irrecoverable receivables.


Derivative financial instruments and hedge accounting


The group uses certain derivative financial instruments to reduce its exposure to interest rate movements.  The group does not hold or use derivative financial instruments for speculative purposes.


Changes In the fair values of derivative financial instruments that are designated and effective as hedges of future cash flows are recognised directly in equity and any ineffective portion is recognised directly in the income statement.  If the cash flow hedge of a firm commitment or forecasted transaction results in the recognition of an asset or liability, then, at the time the asset or liability is recognised, the associated gains or losses on the derivative that had previously been recognised in equity are included in the initial measurement of the asset or liability.  For hedges that do not result In the recognition of an asset or liability amounts deferred in equity are recognised in the income statement in the same period in which the hedged item affects the income statement.


Changes in the fair value of derivative financial instruments that do not qualify for hedge accounting are recognised in the income statement as they arise.


Hedge accounting is discontinued when the hedging instrument expires or is sold, terminated, exercised or no longer qualifies for hedge accounting.  At that time any cumulative gain or loss on the hedging Instrument recognised in equity is retained in equity until the transaction occurs.  If a hedged transaction is no longer expected to occur the net cumulative gain or loss recognised in equity is transferred to the net income or expense for the year.


Income recognition


In the income statement, revenue comprises amounts receivable for goods and services provided in the course of business to customers net of credits and discounts, and is stated net of VAT and other sales taxes.  Sales of goods are recognised, less provision for returns, when goods are delivered and title has passed.  Sales of services are recognised when the stage of completion of the services and the related revenue and costs can be measured reliably.


Sales by associated undertakings are not included in revenue.


Other operating income includes incidental income receivable by the group such as the sale of unsolds (waste), sundry amounts billed to suppliers and sublet income from surplus properties.


Bank interest receivable is accrued on a time basis taking account of the principal outstanding and the interest rate applicable.


Dividend income from investments is recognised when the right to receive payment has been established.


Taxation


Current tax, including UK corporation tax and foreign tax, is provided at amounts expected to be paid (or recovered) using the tax rates and laws that have been enacted or substantively enacted by the balance sheet date.


Full provision is made for the tax effect of temporary differences between the carrying amounts of assets and liabilities in the financial statements and their corresponding tax bases used in the computation of taxable profit, except where these differences arise upon the initial recognition of goodwill.


Deferred tax liabilities are recognised for all taxable temporary differences, except that no provision is made for the unremitted earnings of overseas subsidiaries where there is no commitment to remit such earnings.


Deferred tax assets are recognised for all taxable temporary differences to the extent that it is probable that sufficient future taxable income will be available.  Deferred tax is charged or credited in the income statement except when it relates to items charged or credited to equity, in which case it too is charged or credited directly to equity.


Foreign currencies


Transactions in foreign currencies are translated to the respective functional currencies of group entities at exchange rates at the dates of the transactions.  Monetary assets and liabilities denominated in foreign currencies at the reporting date are retranslated to the functional currency at the exchange rate at that date.  Foreign currency differences arising on retranslation are recognised in profit or loss.


The results of foreign subsidiaries are translated into sterling at the average exchange rate.  Balance sheets are translated at the exchange rates prevailing at the period end.  Exchange differences arising on the consolidation and on long-term funding of subsidiary companies are transferred to the group's translation reserve.  The group has elected that the cumulative translation differences for all foreign operations are deemed to be nil at the date of transition to IFRSs.


Goodwill and fair value adjustments arising on the acquisition of a foreign entity are treated as assets and liabilities of the foreign entity and translated at the closing rate. The group has elected to treat goodwill and fair value adjustments arising on acquisitions before the date of translation to IFRSs as sterling denominated assets and liabilities.


All other exchange differences are dealt with through the income statement.


Retirement benefit (pension) costs


The group provides pension arrangements on a defined contribution basis and costs are charged to the income statement as they fall due.


On 28 May 2009, the Company ceased to be a nominated employer to the DDDDD Holdings Group Pension Fund.


During the time the group operated a defined benefit scheme, the cost of providing benefits was determined using the Projected Unit Credit Method, with actuarial valuations being carried out at each balance sheet date.  The retirement benefit obligation recognised in the balance sheet represented the present value of the defined benefit obligation as reduced by the fair value of scheme assets.  The defined benefit obligation was the amount of future benefit that employees have earned in return for their service In the current and prior periods; that benefit was discounted to determine its present value.  The discount rate was the yield at the reporting date on AA credit-rated bonds that have maturity dates approximating the terms of the group's obligations.


Actuarial gains and losses were recognised In full In the period in which they occurred.  They were not included within the income statement but are instead presented within the statement of recognised income and expense.


Gains or losses on the settlement or curtailment of a defined benefit scheme were recognised in the income statement when the curtailment or settlement occurred.


Long-term incentive schemes


The costs of long-term incentive schemes, where amounts are payable based on business performance over a number of years, are accrued over the lives of said schemes based on an estimate of the final amounts payable which is reviewed at each period end.


Provisions


Provisions are recognised when the group has a present legal or constructive obligation as a result of past events and it is probable that the group will have to settle that obligation.  The provision represents the current best estimate of the net expenditure required to settle the obligation.


Share-based payments


The group has applied the requirements of IFRS 2 Share-based Payment to all share options granted on or after 7 November 2002, including those relating to Savings Related Share Option Schemes, as well as to matching share awards under the Encouraging Executive Share Ownership Scheme and awards under the Long Term Share Plan.


The fair value of share options and share awards is measured at the date of grant.  This fair value is then expensed on a straight-line basis over the vesting period based on the group's estimate of the number of shares that will ultimately vest.

Goodwill has been allocated for impairment testing purposes to business segments.  The group considers its business segments as comprising the lowest level at which goodwill can be allocated.  The group tests annually for impairment or more frequently if there are indicators that goodwill may be impaired.


Division D


As a result of a number of suppliers deciding in March 2009 not to renew their contracts with Division D all goodwill was written off at the half-year.  The gadget division has been discontinued during the period.


Division A


Goodwill allocated to Division A, which is considered to be a group of cash generating units (CGUs) is the aggregate of a number of individual acquisitions.


The major component of goodwill brought forward at 1 October 2005, totalling £5.8m, arose on the acquisition of Widget Direct in December 1999.  A further goodwill balance, £1.6m, arose in October 2004 on the acquisition of Widget  Services in Germany.


Taking account of the current economic environment and other risks, a review of the goodwill has led to a write down of £2.7m in the current period.


Division C


Goodwill allocated to Division C, which is considered to be a group of CGUs, is the aggregate of two individual acquisitions, Widget Support Services in June 2000 and the goodwill of £4.9m arising on the acquisition of MHJ Limited in September 2007.


Taking account of the current economic environment and other risks, a review of the goodwill has led to a write down of £4.7m in the current period.


In determining the levels of goodwill for Division A and Division C the directors were mindful of the valuation reports produced at the time of the reorganisation in May 2009, by independent valuers.  The impairment loss resulted from the carrying amounts of the CGUs being higher than their respective recoverable amounts.


The recoverable amount of the above CGUs has been determined on a value in use basis.  The calculations used cash flow projections based on management forecasts to 2014 with a 2% terminal growth (2008: 2.5%).


The cash flows were projected based on past experience, actual operating results and most recent budgets and management forecasts, which included sales growth ranging from 0% to 6% for the different CGUs.


Future cashflows were discounted using pre-tax rates of between 13.2% for Division C (2008: 11 %) and 12.2% for Division A (2008: 11 %) which the directors consider to be appropriate market participants cost of capital for these businesses.  The discount rates were estimated based on past experience, observed betas of comparable companies and amended according to the conditions relating to each CGU, to reflect relevant risk factors.


The key assumptions underlying the cash flow projections during the forecast period are that the businesses will remain stable and will achieve a modest level of organic growth.  No major changes in operating margins have been assumed and it is also assumed that all major contracts will be retained or else replaced by equivalent new business wins.  Whilst management is confident that its assumptions are appropriate in the light of circumstances at the time of review, it is possible that circumstances may change.  Thus the carrying amount of the CGUs that include goodwill may exceed the recoverable amount calculated on the above basis when the circumstances change further.

27 Retirement benefit schemes 


Defined contribution schemes


The group operates occupational pension schemes for all qualifying employees and all ongoing pension arrangements are on a defined contribution basis.


A total cost of £1 m (2008 £0.7m) was charged to income in respect of contributions payable to these schemes by the group at rates specified in the rules of the various schemes.


As at 30 September 2009, contributions due in respect of the current reporting period that had not been paid over to the schemes amounted to less than £0.1 m (2008 less than £0,1 m).  In addition at 27 September 2008, there was a prepayment of £0.1m in respect of the main UK defined contribution scheme.


Defined benefit schemes


On 28 May 2009, the company ceased to be a nominated employer to the DDDDD Holdings Group Pension Fund (Pension Fund).


The Pension Fund is a defined benefit scheme. It was closed to new entrants with effect from 14 December 1999, pensionable salary increases were limited to inflation increases (subject to a maximum of 5%) with effect from 1 July 2006, and future accrual was terminated with effect from 1 July 2008.


The assets of this fund are held in trust, separately from the assets of the group.


As announced by the Company on 28 May 2009 the group effected a reorganisation that required the consent of the Trustees of the DDDDD Holdings Group Pension Fund, the Pensions Protection Fund (PPF) and the Pensions Regulator.  Pensions Regulator clearance was required in order to ensure that the Pensions Regulator would not exercise its powers to unwind the Reorganisation following the insolvency of DDDDD Subsidiary 5 Limited.


The Pensions Regulator would provide clearance only once satisfied that the PPF had agreed to the terms of the Reorganisation.  Consequently, the negotiations with the PPF, the Trustees and the Pensions Regulator resulted in the Pensions Agreement in which it was agreed to apportion all but a small amount of the Company's pension liability to DDDDD Subsidiary 5 Limited (the principal employer to the Pension Fund).  In addition, it was agreed that the Trustees would subscribe for the new shares conditional only on shareholder approval.  The quantum of the pension liability remaining with the Company was equal to the subscriptions monies payable by the Trustees.


On 3 August 2009 DDDDD Subsidiary 5 Limited went into administration and at that point the Pension Fund was de-recognised by the group and the gain crystallised.


The shareholders approved on 12 October 2009 the issue of the new shares to the Pension Fund.  As the shares had not been issued by the balance sheet date, a further provision for £0.8m was held at the year end in respect of the Company's IAS 19 deficit.  This liability was extinguished after the balance sheet date by the issue of 6,519,493 ordinary shares and 25,623,586 B ordinary shares at nominal value.

Expected long term rate of return on assets

The scheme was comprised of both office based and field based employees, primarily situated in the south of the UK.


To develop the expected long-term rate of return on assets assumption, the group considered the current level of expected returns on risk-free investments (primarily government bonds), the historic level of the risk premium associated with the other asset classes in which the portfolio was invested and the expectations for future returns of each asset class. The expected return for each asset class was then weighted based on the target asset allocation to develop the expected long-term rate of return on assets assumption for the portfolio. This resulted in the selection of the 7.3% assumption (gross of expenses in 2008, net in prior years, as expenses were now included in the liabilities).


Formal actuarial valuation  

The last formal actuarial valuation of the fund was carried out as at 1 July 2007.  The valuation was performed using a market-based approach and the projected unit method.  The main assumptions used to determine the pension cost were a rate of investment return of 7.0% p.a. pre retirement (5.0% p.a. post retirement), salary increases of 3.0% p.a. and pension increases of 3.0% p.a..  At the valuation date the market value of the assets was £51.7m, which represented 87% of the value of the combined benefits that had accrued to members.

30 Share-based payments 


Savings related share options


During the period, no new share options were granted under the  DDDDD Savings Related Share Option Scheme.


Savings related share option schemes are periodically made available to all employees.  The options are typically provided at an exercise price equal to 80% of the quoted market price at the date of grant and may vest over a period of three or five years.  If the options remain unexercised after a period of six months after the date of vesting, the options expire.


Long Term Incentive Plan 2006


No new long term incentive plan options were granted during the period.


Previous options granted under long term incentive plans were typically provided at an exercise price equal to the quoted market price at the date of grant and vested over a period of three years. If the options remain unexercised after a period of ten years after the date of grant the options expire.

Encouraging Executive Share Ownership Scheme


Certain executives were invited to invest all or part of their net (after tax) bonus in Company shares.  If the executive then remains employed within the group for three years from the date of acquisition of these shares the Company will transfer additional shares to the executive on a one-for-one basis.


During the year to 30 September 2009 111,800 new shares were purchased by executives under the terms of the above scheme and 4,500 shares were transferred to executives who qualified for the additional shares based on previous purchases during the period ended 1 October 2005. The cumulative total of shares purchased under the scheme and still held by executives as at 30 September 2009 was 137,163.


The Long Term Share Plan 2008


The LTSP 2008, approved by the shareholders at the AGM in February 2008, was introduced to ensure that long-term incentives have clear and stretching targets, provide strong alignment with shareholders, are tailored to the Company's circumstances and are cost effective.


During the year ended 30 September 2009, awards over a maximum of 949,936 shares were granted to senior executives in the group, contingent upon the group's earnings per share performance in the financial year ended 2011.


In total, 1,585,569 shares have been awarded under the LTSP.  With the administration of DDDDD Subsidiary 5 Limited on 3 August 2009 a number of executives left the group.  Together with other leavers, the impact on the awards is a reduction of 531,768 leaving 1,053,801 shares outstanding.


However it is the view of the Remuneration Committee that the profit targets are unlikely to be met given the reduced size of the group.  Accordingly, no provisions have been made for any awards under the LTSP.

33 Financial risks  


(a) Financial strategy and risk management objectives


The group's overall objective when managing financial risk is to safeguard its ability to continue as a going concern in order to provide returns for shareholders and benefits to other stakeholders.  To this end, the group seeks to maintain an optimal level of net debt as part of the long term capital structure of the entity.


Market risks are inherent in the use of debt capital; interest rate cash flow risk for example, on top of which in the course of its normal activities the group is routinely exposed to a variety of other financial risks.. For the group, these primarily include credit risk on trade receivables, foreign exchange risk and overall liquidity risk.


Financial risk management is carried out centrally under written policies approved by the Board of Directors. Under the supervision of the Group Finance Director, the group finance function identifies and evaluates financial risks in close co-operation with the group's three operating divisions.


The use of simple financial derivatives is considered in order to hedge specific financial risks where cost effective to do so.  The group does not enter into, or trade, financial Instruments, including derivative financial instruments for speculative purposes.


Further Information about specific risks is given below.


(b) Interest rate cash flow risk


All interest rates on borrowings are floating rate with the rate based on the relevant national bank rate.  As a result, the group is exposed to a degree of interest rate cash flow risk.  The group constantly monitors this exposure with a view to putting In place suitable hedging mechanisms where appropriate.


As at 30 September 2009, there was no interest rate hedging mechanism in place.


(c) Foreign exchange risk


The vast majority of the group's transactions, receivables and payables are sterling denominated.  However, the group operates internationally and is exposed to foreign exchange risk arising from various exposures primarily in respect of the euro and US dollar.  Foreign exchange risk hence arises on certain future commercial transactions, recognised assets and liabilities and net investments in foreign operations.


During the year ended 30 September 2009 the euro strengthened from approximately 1.26 to 1.09 per pound sterling.  This was the main factor behind the group's recognising net exchange gains of £0.2m in the consolidated income statement ( note 4).  In addition, it also added approximately £0.1 m to the net profits of overseas entities converted into sterling at the average exchange rate, as against what they would have been at last year's rates.  In future, the group would expect similar exchange rate movements to impact on the group's results to a broadly similar extent.


In magnitude, the main exposure to exchange rate fluctuations is on the group's investments in foreign operations, whose net assets are exposed to foreign currency translation risk.  Gains or losses on the net investment in foreign operations are reported in the SORIE, with the net gain of £0.8m reported in the current year also primarily arising from the aforementioned strengthening of the euro.


As each overseas entity is able to operate on a stand alone basis and also given the broad degree of matching of currency payables and receivables in the group generally, the group does not envisage that any reasonably foreseeable movement in exchange rates will lead to a material cash flow exposure.


At the present time, therefore, the group does not consider it cost effective to hedge foreign exchange risks and no such arrangements were in place during either the current or preceding financial periods.


(d) Credit risk


Credit risk arises from cash and cash equivalents, as well as credit exposures to trade receivables.  Further details are given in notes 16 and 17.


The group manages credit risk by a constant process of credit checking and credit scoring, establishing individual credit limits for both cash and deposit counterparties and also trade customers.


(e) Liquidity risk


The group's management remain critically alert to liquidity risk invests significant resources in the forecasting and management of its cash Liquidity risk (also called funding risk) is the risk that an entity will not have sufficient funds available to meet Its financial liabilities, including scheduled payments of deferred consideration. as they fall due.  The group invests significant resources in the forecasting and management of its cash flows, over both short and long term time horizons.  As the group is cash generative, its liquidity risk is considered to be minimal.  The group's cash generation allows it to meet all commitments as they fall due.

34 Capital management 


Capital is primarily managed at individual entity level with the overall objective being to foster a collectively strong capital base that will provide a stable level of return to group shareholders and debt providers as well as to maintain overall investor, creditor and market confidence.  An optimal level of net debt forms part of the long term capital structure of the group so as to facilitate and sustain the continuing development of the business.


Neither the Company nor any of its subsidiaries is subject to externally imposed capital requirements.

37 Key Judgements and potential uncertainties


Judgements


In applying the group's accounting policies the Directors are often required to make judgements.  Those judgements which have had the most significant effect on the amounts recognised in the financial statements, and to which the Directors believe it is appropriate to draw the reader's attention, are summarised below:


Valuation of constituent businesses


Whilst the value of the constituent businesses of the group is a matter of considerable commercial sensitivity, the accounting rules require the directors to consider the carrying value for the purposes of the annual report.  In order to effect the reorganisation of the group in May of 2009, the Board of Directors appointed independent valuers to establish a third party view of the value of the businesses at that time.  The range of those valuations reflected, inter alia, the considerable uncertainties surrounding the businesses at the time, all of which are now resolved.  The Board has nonetheless taken a prudent view and, mindful that the balance sheet is not a valuation statement, has reflected those valuations in these accounts.


Uncertainties


In preparing the financial statements the Directors are also required to make estimates and assumptions about matters that can be uncertain as they are subject to external factors.  The Directors have reviewed these, and all other assumptions and estimates used in the preparation of the financial statements, and do not believe that there is a significant risk of a material adjustment arising within the next financial year to the carrying amount of any assets or liabilities as a result of any reasonably likely change In these assumptions and estimates.
